commitResults.messageBody:
Update UserGuide.md to fix table formatting and standardise naming of
clients.

Find command searches only by name.

A find command that gives the option to search by tags is more
user-friendly and gives the user more freedom, because users might want
to look up groups of users based on a certain user defined criteria.

Let's
* change the FindCommandParser to split command arguments by
CLISyntax prefixes into an ArgumentMultimap
* give ArgumentMultimap the functionality to test if there is only one
prefix stored, and return it
* update the find command to use the appropriate predicate to filter
the address book based on the search type, which is determined by the
prefix found

Splitting the arguments to the find command by prefixes will make the
code easily extensible in the future, should we expand on the find
command by allowing other search conditions as well

Add toString method to Command Result to facilitate easier debugging
commitResults.messageBody:
Commands are tested using the assertCommandSuccess abstraction, which
tests if a command is successfully executed by comparing the expected
CommandResult and reuslting Model with the actual CommandResult and
model produced by running the command.

Giving CommandResult a toString method will smoothen out the process
of debugging test cases, since with a toString method, we will be
able to tell the difference between the expected output and the actual
output at a glance, instead of seeing the locations of the two
CommandResult objects, which is rather cryptic and not very helpful.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add hasOnlySpecifiedPrefixPresent method to ArgumentMultimap class
commitResults.messageBody:
There are several commands that are only able to accept in only
certain parameters only, such as sort only accepting name, income or
meeting date, and find only accepting name, tags and plans.

Abstracting out all these checks for valid parameters will reduce
duplicate code and improve code quality in the spirit of the DRY
principle.

Let's:
[X] create a hasOnlySpecifiedPrefixPresent method in the ArgumentMultimap
class that checks that only valid parameters are present
[ ] abstract out the code that checks for valid parameters by replacing
them with the hasOnlySpecifiedPrefixPresent method

commitResults.messageBody:
AddressBook, ModelManager, and UniquePersonList all have cryptic and
therefore not very helpful outputs when printed or logged, which
makes debugging difficult.

Add toString methods to these classes to have an output that is
descriptive of the class contents, and is easily comparable with
diffing operations.

commitResults.messageBody:
Sort command will inform the user that a sort is performed but not
perform any sorting if either:
* more than one parameter is passed as argument to the command, or
* a string containing a paramter flag (eg n/, i/ or m/) is passed but
contains other noise (eg. sort plan/time is accepted as a valid command
as it contains n/, but no sorting is performed)

Use switch case in SortCommandParser to sanitise inputs and ensure only
correct inputs are accepted.
